{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508914"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:10:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:10:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11358"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11358"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.31,0.07,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43659"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4003"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28666"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1415"},{"type":"tags","id":"2170"},{"type":"tags","id":"2250"},{"type":"tags","id":"4632"},{"type":"tags","id":"5617"},{"type":"tags","id":"5619"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6273"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43659"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man is undergoing a laparoscopic hiatal hernia repair and gastric fundoplication. He has a medical history of GORD, obesity, hypertension and benign prostatic enlargement. His medications include omeprazole, amlodipine and enalapril. Approximately one hour into the case, the surgeon notes that the man\u0027s abdomen is stiff. His temperature has risen to 38.6\u00baC and his end-tidal carbon dioxide is 65 mmHg. He was last given a dose of neuromuscular blocker around twenty minutes ago.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following agents is most likely to have caused this?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sevoflurane","Rocuronium","Atracurium","Propofol","Fentanyl"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Esevoflurane\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient has presented with signs highly suggestive of malignant hyperthermia. Volatile liquid anaesthetics such as sevoflurane, desflurane and isoflurane are known to be associated with malignant hyperthermia. Suxamethonium, a depolarizing neuromuscular blocker, is also a common inciting agent.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERocuronium\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eatracurium\u003C/strong\u003E are non-depolarising neuromuscular blockers and are not generally implicated in cases of malignant hyperthermia. Anaphylaxis is the most concerning serious side-effect of administration of these agents, although this is fairly rare.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropofol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common anaesthetic induction agent and is not associated with malignant hyperthermia. One of the most common side effects is hypotension and thus, propofol is best avoided in patients with haemodynamic instability. It also commonly causes pain on injection. It has intrinsic anti-emetic properties, making it a good choice for total intravenous anaesthesia in patients with a history of postoperative nausea and vomiting.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFentanyl\u003C/strong\u003E is an opioid and is commonly used for intraoperative analgesia. It is also not associated with malignant hyperthermia. Side effects include sedation, respiratory depression, nausea and vomiting, as well as constipation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Recognition of malignant hyperthermia in the intraoperative setting and knowledge of common causes","Volatile liquid anaesthetics such as sevoflurane, desflurane and isoflurane, as well as depolarising neuromuscular blocker suxamethonium are known to be associated with malignant hyperthermia."],"references":["Glahn K, Ellis F, Halsall P, M\u00fcller C, Snoeck M, Urwyler A, et al. Recognizing and managing a malignant hyperthermia crisis: guidelines from the European Malignant Hyperthermia Group. British Journal of Anaesthesia\u202f: BJA. 2010;105(4):417\u201320. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20837722/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28666"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11358"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28666"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-25T12:40:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-25T12:40:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4003"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43659"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty